00:42.360 --> 00:49.980
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. Howard Waldrop is a science fiction writer
whose stories began appearing in the early 1970s, and he's written some

00:49.980 --> 00:57.660
remarkably good ones. His reputation as one of science fiction's finest short
story writers is growing. Waldrop's The Ugly Chickens won a Nebula Award in

00:57.660 --> 01:07.940
1981, and God's Hooks was a 1983 Nebula finalist. Ike at the Mike is a 1983 Hugo
finalist. Waldrop wrote for fanzines as a teenager, but finally he was inspired

01:07.940 --> 01:17.380
to write science fiction. Here he tells us what inspired him. Well, actually, if
you want to know, everybody has a story like this, but I read Lin Carter's

01:17.380 --> 01:27.060
Wizard of Lemuria, and I said if he can get that published, I can write, I can
get that, you know, I can get my stuff published. You know, it's real obvious.

01:27.260 --> 01:33.780
Like, I mean, everybody I think has a story about that. They read something
after they've been reading this stuff for 20 years. They finally read something

01:33.780 --> 01:42.080
that just pushes their buttons and says, that's garbage, you know, and I can
write better than that. Even when you're 18 years old, you say, I can write

01:42.080 --> 01:49.220
better than that. And you set out to prove it, and a lot of people set out to
prove it, write a story, and like submit it or don't submit it, just write the

01:49.220 --> 01:54.780
story to prove they can write a story, you know, and I'd already been writing a
story, so essentially is I got serious.

02:03.280 --> 02:12.640
Waldrop's first professional sale was a story called Lunchbox. We asked him how
he initially got published. Essentially, I had been trying to get published

02:12.640 --> 02:23.660
since 1966, been serious about it, 65 and 66, and I'd been publishing in
fanzines all along, stories in fanzines, and I just kept sending the stories out

02:23.660 --> 02:32.500
until finally one of them sold. I mean, there was no problem breaking in as
such. I mean, it wasn't like a conscious thing saying, this is the one I'm going

02:32.500 --> 02:39.200
to break in with or I'm going to write a story to break in. It was just I'd been
sending them out and getting them back until one day I sent one out and it

02:39.200 --> 02:48.680
didn't come back, you know. Check came back. And that's, you know, it was like
I'd been writing for fanzines all along and comic scripts and things like that.

02:49.280 --> 02:58.040
And the story just came. I mean, when it was time for it to sell, it sold.
Lunchbox details the fate of the first Viking lander shortly after it touches

02:58.040 --> 03:06.680
down on Mars. Since the story was written prior to the actual Viking landing but
was published after the landing took place, we asked Waldrop if any changes had

03:06.680 --> 03:17.780
to be made in the interim. I sold that story in 1969, or not in 69, in 70, and I
sold it four days, or I got the letter four days after I was drafted in the

03:17.780 --> 03:25.720
Army. And, but because John Campbell, it was sold analog, and because John
Campbell died in the meantime and everything was in an uproar at Street &

03:25.720 --> 03:38.020
Smith for about, or CondÃ© Nast for six months or so, Ben Bova wrote me a letter
in 1972 and said, I'm changing all, originally it was called Voyager. If you

03:38.020 --> 03:45.900
remember, the Viking stuff was all called Voyager, and the whole story was
talking about the Voyager lander and all this kind of stuff. And Ben Bova wrote

03:45.900 --> 03:55.120
and says, it's okay if I change Voyager to Viking so he won't look like a jerk.
And I said, why sure, Ben, you know, anything you want. And, you know, because

03:55.120 --> 04:01.600
the technology, they changed the, they changed the term, you know, the
terminology in the meantime. And, you know, I'd been in the Army, and what was

04:01.600 --> 04:11.320
that? You know, I was guarding PXs and stuff, you know, and, you know, I hadn't
been kept up on the change in terminology in the meantime, you know, but yes, it

04:11.320 --> 04:23.180
was, it preceded, there were several prototype models of the, essentially what
became the Viking lander, all competing for the contract in the late 60s. And

04:23.180 --> 04:34.780
the Voyager thing was one of them, and I've got a picture I visited Langley for
one of the mock-ups of the original Voyager thing, which was slightly, it looked

04:34.780 --> 04:45.420
much the same as the Viking eventually was, but had, you know, longer arm and
all this kind of stuff, you know. But, anyway, yeah, it preceded the program, so

04:45.420 --> 04:52.780
that's why, you know, the change to Viking was, you know, like, fitted into the
story. More with Howard Waldrop on our next show.

