06:26.720 --> 06:33.980
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Science fiction writer Howard Waldrop
collaborated with several writers on short stories in the 1970s, including

06:33.980 --> 06:42.720
Stephen Utley, Buddy Saunders, George Proctor, and George Martin. We asked
Waldrop why these collaborations took place. There was a group of us, and we

06:42.720 --> 06:53.260
all, it's amazing that it happened. We were all from Texas, living in Texas, and
we all published our first story within like six or eight months of each other.

06:53.340 --> 07:03.620
It was amazing. It just happened that way. And we all got to meet each other at
conventions within like six months of our first stories being published. And we

07:03.620 --> 07:11.400
were all writing at the same time. We were all serious about this stuff. We were
going to take over. And one of the ways we did it was we started collaborating

07:11.400 --> 07:19.880
with each other. And we'd do stories on our own, but then we'd also do stories
that we couldn't do on our own with the other people. And it wasn't a conscious

07:19.880 --> 07:25.780
effort on anybody's part. I think it's just one of those things that just
happened. You know, we were just all writing at the same time. We were all right

07:25.780 --> 07:33.080
there. Like Buddy was my landlord. You know, he owned one half of Duplex and I
was in the other. And he, of course, he got me into comics fandom ten years

07:33.080 --> 07:43.240
before that anyway. And some of us were friends. Some of us met each other and
became friends and things like that. And it's just that we just sparked each

07:43.240 --> 07:51.520
other, you know. If you had something you were doing and you got through with it
and you weren't quite ready to do something else, you could always, you know, do

07:51.520 --> 08:02.160
a collaboration with Buddy or with Proctor or with, you know, anything like
that. And, like, we just, there must have been, in a space of about two years,

08:02.160 --> 08:12.040
there must have been 35 or 40 stories come out of the various collaborations,
you know, two and sometimes three-way collaborations with people, you know. It

08:12.040 --> 08:18.020
was amazing. And it's amazing that it happened. And it's amazing that we got so
much done on our own, too, besides doing all that.

08:25.220 --> 08:33.360
One of these collaborations, A Voice and Bitter Weeping, written with Buddy
Saunders, was expanded to a novel, The Texas-Israeli War, 1999. We asked Waldrop

08:33.360 --> 08:45.760
how this transformation occurred. We originally wrote that story before I'd sold
Lunchbox, even. Buddy and I did this 10,000-word novella, or novelette, in

08:45.760 --> 08:55.740
alternate chapters, like, you know, as in the novel, as in the first, like, 50
pages of the novel. We tried to sell that thing everywhere, and it would not

08:55.740 --> 09:07.920
sell. You know, it got up to the point where the battleship, the battle with the
battleship, or the cruiser, in Dallas. That was where the thing ended. And it

09:07.920 --> 09:14.440
wouldn't sell anywhere. And I went in the Army, and Buddy quit trying to market
it while I was in the Army. Well, when I came out of the Army, and I started

09:14.440 --> 09:23.480
selling stories and all this stuff, and everybody started selling stories, Buddy
started writing again. He also took A Voice in Bitter Weeping, took all my parts

09:23.480 --> 09:33.100
out of it, in other words, half the story, just by leaving the parts he'd
written in, and sold it first thing off to Galaxy. And, okay, and then he sold

09:33.100 --> 09:42.060
it to Galaxy. Judy-Lynn Del Ray was the assistant editor at Galaxy, and had just
been hired by Ballantine Books as her SF editor. The last thing she saw before

09:42.060 --> 09:51.020
she left Galaxy was our story, and she liked it. And she wrote it, and she said,
I like this story a lot. Do you think you could come up with an outline for a

09:51.020 --> 09:59.360
novel? And if you do, I'll offer you so much and so much. And we went, oh, wow,
you know. So we said, not only do we have an outline, we sat down and, like,

09:59.540 --> 10:07.460
continued the outline as the book goes, like in one night, we said, not only do
we have an outline, but the first 10,000 words are already written. You know,

10:07.720 --> 10:14.120
and just like that. We just stuck my parts back in, the alternate chapters back
in. We had 10,000 words of the book already, and all we had to do was write

10:14.120 --> 10:23.980
another 45,000 words, you know. And they wrote back, you know, they accepted the
outline, gave us a contract, and that was, you know, we wrote the book. It was a

10:23.980 --> 10:31.280
stroke of luck. It was just a stroke of luck. We were, it was at the right place
at the right time, you know. Two weeks before or two weeks later, that wouldn't

10:31.280 --> 10:34.500
have happened, probably. More with Howard Waldrop on our next show.

