12:05.840 --> 12:14.700
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. In 1976, a collaboration between Howard
Waldrop and Stephen Utley produced the Nebula finalist novelette Custer's Last

12:14.700 --> 12:22.600
Jump. Custer's Last Jump is an immensely detailed alternate world story which
begins with the American Civil War. In this alternate history, both the Union

12:22.600 --> 12:31.440
and the Confederacy have airplanes which figure heavily in the war. During the
conflict, the Oglala Sioux leader Crazy Horse manages to acquire and secrete a

12:31.440 --> 12:40.960
few planes himself. In 1876, these planes are used in a climactic battle against
Custer. Waldrop explains how this story was written. Utley had always been a

12:40.960 --> 12:51.560
Custer freak. He knew all about all that stuff. I'd always been an airplane
freak, so I knew all about the airplane stuff. And we started one night in 1972.

12:52.300 --> 13:05.360
It was like November of 1972. We started playing Can You Top This? on a
typewriter. And so Utley wrote this section about part of the second part, the

13:05.360 --> 13:14.240
Collier's article. He wrote about two pages of that, and he read it to me over
the phone. And about an hour later, I rang him back up and read the first three

13:14.240 --> 13:25.800
pages of the part of the Smithsonian report about Crazy Horse's airplane. And we
just went crazy from there, you know? And like the story was written in like six

13:25.800 --> 13:33.780
days or something like that. I did a tremendous amount of research in the time
between the time we started the story and the time we finished it, you know? One

13:33.780 --> 13:44.300
of the things was it was written in the alternate. I wrote the airplane part.
Utley wrote the Collier's article. Steve wrote the Twain part because he'd

13:44.300 --> 13:54.840
always been fascinated by Mark Twain. And then I wrote the Testament of Black
Man's Hand, you know, that Twain transcribes in the story. And then we both sat

13:54.840 --> 14:03.340
down and wrote the bibliography together, you know, did all this stuff in the
bibliography. And it came out, I think it took about a week to write the story.

14:03.440 --> 14:13.560
But it was because we, both of us knew certain parts, you know? You already had
done research in certain areas that we could write the story and use the other

14:13.560 --> 14:20.720
research we did as we wrote it to finish it. But we did research, but we already
had a lot of research, too.

14:31.420 --> 14:40.180
All of Waldrop's stories are characterized by a lot of details. This prompted us
to ask Waldrop how much research he does prior to his writing a story. It's like

14:40.180 --> 14:49.740
everybody says, and I know it's true, I research too much. I research everything
too much. Every story I write, I research a whole bunch and then don't use half

14:49.740 --> 15:00.600
of it, you know? Don't use a third of it, usually something like that. I like
certain research that I want to do on my own when I'm not sure what I'm doing.

15:00.920 --> 15:11.760
So I read a whole lot about the whole subject. And a lot of that works its way
back into the story. When I know exactly what I want to do in a story, then I

15:11.760 --> 15:19.900
get real specific and that research is not as much fun. You know, because you're
saying, I need to know exactly when or exactly what or something like that. You

15:19.900 --> 15:26.360
know, and that's not because then you've got to look. Whereas if you don't know
anything, not anything, but you don't know much about the field, you can just go

15:26.360 --> 15:33.880
and get everything on it and just start going through it and reading it and
coming across fascinating little nuggets and stuff like that to use, you know?

15:34.580 --> 15:44.080
But I do too much research. I do way too much research for every story. And it's
like sometimes the research will take a month and writing a story will take two

15:44.080 --> 15:56.160
days. You know, it's like... We asked Waldrop if he considers this extra research
to be wasted effort. It's never wasted. It's only wasteful in the sense that I

15:56.160 --> 16:04.200
could possibly be doing the next thing down the line while I'm still even doing
the research on one thing. You know, I could already be through with the story

16:04.200 --> 16:11.520
and have it. But I do the research and it just shows up in the story.

16:12.220 --> 16:14.520
We'll have more with Howard Waldrop on our next show.

