17:47.340 --> 17:55.300
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. The 1981 Nebula Award for Best Novelette
went to Howard Waldrop's The Ugly Chickens. Waldrop has had several works which

17:55.300 --> 18:02.860
made the final ballot in the Nebula voting, but The Ugly Chickens is his first
winner. We asked him if he considers this his best work. The Terry to whom

18:02.860 --> 18:15.000
Waldrop prefers is noted editor Terry Carr. I have not mixed feelings, but I had
no idea when I wrote Ugly Chickens how good it was or not. I hadn't written a

18:15.000 --> 18:24.760
story for about six months when I wrote that. I was doing other stuff and I was
working on research on other things, and I hadn't written an actual story. So

18:24.760 --> 18:33.220
when I finally wrote Ugly Chickens, I didn't know if it was any good or not. I
really didn't. I couldn't tell anymore. I'd worked on it so long. You know, I

18:33.220 --> 18:40.260
did all this research for the thing. Like, I did six months of research for it.
It's way too long for a story. And then I wrote the story and I didn't know if

18:40.260 --> 18:49.660
the story was any good or not. And then I sent it off to Terry. And, like, the
thing was that Terry at the time was taking a lot of medicine. He had wrenched

18:49.660 --> 18:57.840
his back and he was taking a lot of medicine and reading for Universe at the
same time. Universe filled up. And he said, I'd like to take it, but Universe is

18:57.840 --> 19:04.920
filled up and all this stuff. And I said, okay. And about that time, Marta
Randall called. You know, and said, hey, I just heard from Terry about the story

19:04.920 --> 19:12.080
and I want it real bad. And will you take twice as much money for it? You know,
and I said, oh, sure, right. You know, so she ran down the hill and got the

19:12.080 --> 19:20.620
story from Terry and brought, you know, and sent me a contract. And, like, two
nights later, I walk in the house and it's 12:30 at night and the phone rings.

19:20.780 --> 19:31.680
And he says, Howard, this is Terry. And I could just see dollars flying out the
window. I knew exactly what was going to happen, you know. And, like, he had

19:31.680 --> 19:41.180
gotten off his medicine. And one of the stories he had been promised wasn't
delivered. And the person said, I can't do it, you know. And he wanted the story

19:41.180 --> 19:49.740
back real bad. And, like, he was trying, you know, he was trying politely to get
the story back for less money than Marta was going to pay me and all this kind

19:49.740 --> 20:00.160
of stuff. Anyway, I had no idea whether, at the time, whether the story was any
good or it was just Marta and Terry were not functioning at their, you know, top

20:00.160 --> 20:12.520
flight level or something. I don't know, but I always try to hope that the next
story I write or one down the line is going to be my best, you know. And there's

20:12.520 --> 20:23.120
just no, you know. I like Ugly Chickens. It still holds up, I think, real well,
if that's what you mean. I went back and reread it about three months ago, and

20:23.120 --> 20:31.520
it was still a good story, which is all you can hope for, because some of them
aren't, you know. Or not that they're not good, it's that they're not like you

20:31.520 --> 20:40.400
remembered them or wanted them to be. The final 1983 Nebula Ballot featured a
Waldrop story, God's Hooks. It's based on the meeting between two monumental

20:40.400 --> 20:49.620
literary figures, Izaak Walton and John Bunyan. And it's amazing that nobody had
stuck those together, and because they did, any time you look at a survey of

20:49.620 --> 20:58.100
English literature, the two books that are unclassifiable, the only two
unclassifiable books, in other words, there were like biographies, and there

20:58.100 --> 21:06.000
were like histories, and there were beginnings of novels, and there were poetry
and plays and all that. But the only two unclassifiable books they talk about

21:06.000 --> 21:16.260
are Pilgrim's Progress and The Complete Angler. You know, those are two totally,
totally, you know, classical books, and they're not like any other books written

21:16.260 --> 21:26.740
that century or before or since, you know. It amazed me that nobody had put the
two together. And the obvious way to put the two together was, you know, I was

21:26.740 --> 21:34.380
sitting there one day and I said, I was doing research on Walton and Bunyan and
all this, and I said, Walton fishes in the slew of despond. You know, it's

21:34.380 --> 21:43.180
obvious, you know, right? You know, it's just totally obvious, you know. And it
amazed me that nobody had done it before, especially a British writer. You know,

21:43.260 --> 21:53.380
especially a British writer. There were lots of people who were capable of doing
that, you know. And nobody had done it, and it was amazing. More with Howard

21:53.380 --> 21:54.420
Waldrop on our next show.

