23:27.340 --> 23:35.520
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Howard Waldrop's story, Mary Margaret Road
Grader, was a Nebula finalist short story in 1976. Centered in the desert

23:35.520 --> 23:42.360
southwest, Mary Margaret Road Grader portrays a rather bleak future. Their
protagonists are American Indians, and they occasionally have get-togethers,

23:42.360 --> 23:51.380
which are highlighted by contests involving vehicles, something akin to tractor
pulls. Waldrop told us a story just came to them in a flash. I'd always been

23:51.380 --> 23:53.540
fascinated with Indians,

23:56.080 --> 24:05.160
and the Mary Margaret Road Grader was another one of those stories, like Mono No
Aware. There are about three I've done that just came to me in a flash. I mean,

24:05.240 --> 24:14.740
it was just... I'd done research on Indians for years. I'd taken a course in
college in American Indian literature

24:15.380 --> 24:28.740
and things like that. But the story itself just came in a flash one morning,
early one morning, you know. And I wrote it like in a day, you know, the whole

24:28.740 --> 24:37.680
thing, beginning to end, you know, and I knew exactly like it came to me, the
entire story. It's really amazing. It's really a rare thing, and like writers

24:37.680 --> 24:46.220
usually have about, in their whole career, that happens about twice or three
times, you know, and I've used up two of mine. I know, I know, you know. It's

24:46.220 --> 24:55.040
really nice when it happens. But just all the research I've done through the
years just tumbled out, you know, while I was writing the story. Here he

24:55.040 --> 25:03.320
explains what made the story come to him. It was essentially, I guess, a lot of,
you know, a lot of stuff had just been running around in my mind for months and

25:03.320 --> 25:12.260
months. And what triggered it was that I got up early one morning. I was
visiting a friend in Austin and sleeping on the couch, and I got up and I put on

25:12.260 --> 25:21.400
Bridge Over Troubled Water by Simon and Garfunkel. And between the opening notes
and like the end of the first verse, the whole story just went, you know, and I

25:21.400 --> 25:31.700
said, wow, you know, this is great. And I guess it was, I mean, if you go back
and if you listen to Bridge Over Troubled Water and you read the story, there's

25:31.700 --> 25:40.260
no common element at all. It's just something in the, I guess, in the feel or
the mood of the song at the time that just brought all that out. 1983's Hugo

25:40.260 --> 25:48.780
Finals include a Waldrop story, Ike at the Mike, which appeared in Omni. This
story has an interesting background. Me and Lee were watching The Heroes of Rock

25:48.780 --> 26:02.100
and Roll, Volume 2 or whatever it was, and they did like a 30-second bit at the
end showing the two heroes of the 50s, which were Elvis Presley and Dwight David

26:02.100 --> 26:14.140
Eisenhower, and it just showed clips from both their lives, you know, right? And
I said, wow, you know, a world where Ike is the musician and Elvis is the

26:14.140 --> 26:26.020
politician, you know? And I tried to give the story to Chad Oliver and Louis
Shiner. They wanted to collaborate at the time. And I tried to give the story to

26:26.020 --> 26:34.080
them. And I said, okay, because Chad's a jazz music, you know, fan, has been
from way back, and Lou knows everything there is to know about Presley. He wrote

26:34.080 --> 26:42.600
a book on Presley at one time. And I tried to just give them the idea. I said,
look, Ike is a jazz musician, Presley's a politician. Come on. You know, do the

26:42.600 --> 26:50.600
story, send it off, make a lot of money, you know? Right? And he said, we just
can't get past the idea of Ike as a musician. You know, they just couldn't do

26:50.600 --> 27:00.340
it. They just couldn't force themselves. You know, I mean, Chad is too close to
jazz to desecrate it like that. And I guess Lou is too close to Presley to, you

27:00.340 --> 27:11.180
know, see the possibilities in politics for Presley. But once they wouldn't take
it, I said, well, hell, I'm going to have to write it myself, you know? So I sat

27:11.180 --> 27:22.720
down and wrote it, you know? It's like you, it's just one of those ideas that
bothers you until you write it, you know? I mean, and once I knew I had to write

27:22.720 --> 27:30.840
it, then I sat down and I did just enough research on Ike and just enough on
Presley to know about how they would be probably about it and wrote the story.

27:31.400 --> 27:35.620
Howard Waldrop's stories will certainly grace Hugo and Nebula ballots for many
years to come.

